column1: 274128;instagram;2018-10-25 11:12:01;FALSE;"i am saddened & hurt by a recent #metoo allegations on a person who is an actor par excellence
column2: a real life gentleman and a true patriot. yes i‚Äôm talking about actor/director arjun sarja sir.  i had an excellent experience playing an army doctor under his direction in premabaraha. being the perfectionist that he is
column3: he had given my script a month in advance for me to practice them to perfection. on the day of shoot
column4: despite me telling him that i was good with my dialougues
column5: he insisted that practice with a real life medical professional representative several times to get it spot on. it made perfect sense and infact my practices with the medical professional enabled me to correct any pronunciation fallacies i had with the medical terms. i saw the value in these practices and realized why arjun sir recommended them. throughout the shooting i marveled at how well arjun sir was taking care of his entire team of stars and technicians. he treated all with equal respect and was always found supporting and nurturing his team. i really salute this well-rounded gentleman
column6: it was a good learning experience for me. he has acted in over 150 movies in 5 languages & never had any allegation against him until this recent one. it's been 2 years since i have worked with this gentleman & till date i talk about my great experience with everyone i meet.

column1: 274265;instagram;2018-10-25 07:49:23;FALSE;"serious convo covered with a selfie. i was talking with a friend today about rape culture and sexual assault. he has always been a protector of women and taught me a lot about how to defend myself/fight off an attacker. i am so thankful for his wisdom and training and pushing me to push my limits. i thanked him the other day and his response was
column2: ""you've always been able to take care of yourself.""

column1: after sitting with those words a while
column4: i've still been raped 5 times and sexually assaulted (actually touched) more times than i can remember. i've always been tough and have never been an ""easy target"" but it still happened; i can't help but to think of the women that didn't grow up fighting like i did
column5: that simply don't know what they're capable of and i think i want to figure out a way to change that. i want to figure out a way to teach women how to defend themselves
column6: possibly train to carry a concealed firearm or knife. show them that they have a voice and should use it without hesitation. i want to make them feel empowered and capable. idk

column4: i was ‚Äòshe‚Äô. my work is a narration of my emotional struggle being a survivor of sexual abuse mainly. it is a statement about psychological and emotional impact of abuse on children as well as adults. our social taboos does not allow women as well as men to raise a voice about their sufferings which makes it more suffocating. we don't have a way out of this because we don't have any one to listen or understand. .

column1: 274405;instagram;2018-10-25 04:54:43;FALSE;"the following incident happened with a friend and is narrated by her. the opinion on the movement is described by her point of the view. ‚Ä¢
i have pretty scarring memories of my grandparents. they're said to be the most loving people
column2: but not in my case. just thinking about them makes me want to crawl under my skin. i hate it. my grandfather started sexually assaulting me ever since i was six. i knew it was wrong. he used call me in washroom at quiet times of the night and pull his dick out and force me to touch it. he is a well known and well respected man in the city. my grandma was aware of it but chose to kept quiet whenever i complained it to her. the abuse went on until i moved to canada. i haven't seen him in four years and i never wish to face him again. even on calls
column3: he acts so concerned about me and my health and he keeps on asking me about why am i so afraid of him. he thinks that i have forgotten the scars he's given me in these four years. i am horrified for life. my best friend gave me the confidence to break this news to my parents. i didn't want to because i thought they would kill me
column4: i come from a extremely conservative muslim family so you know the drill. i kept on thinking about it for the longest time and finally told my mom the news
column5: her reaction was totally unexpected! she said that she's extremely sorry for what happened and that i should've told her earlier. she's planning to break the news to our dad and i am hoping a strict action would be taken against him and my grandma. ‚Ä¢people have made out sexual assault to be so casual in south asian countries that it really sucks to stand up for yourself. the whole #metoo movement is more important than people think it is. it has prepared women like us who kept quiet for so long to speak up and not be afraid of the consequences! it's hard to prove the legitimacy of it because there's no physical proof but honestly the mental scars these kind of abuse leaves you with is proof enough in my opinion. instead of doubting
column6: i hope people were kind enough to understand the perspective. it's not about attention
column7: people have better ways to do it.it's high time people stop doubting and start taking action.";;en;#MeToo;;;;;0;;unfinished.scribbles;Husaina üí´;;0;False;1;0;0;32;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/c14fb43bdbd743607516bfe9765c7570/5D1CE981/t51.2885-15/e35/44489562_2685915344759323_6985245797382809407_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"the following incident happened with a friend and is narrated by her. the opinion on the movement is described by her point of the view. ‚Ä¢

column1: 274507;instagram;2018-10-25 02:40:50;FALSE;"you may think it is not abuse if you're not being hurt physically. but emotional and verbal abuses exist and are equally bad. they could even be a cue for physical abuse.

i went through a harrowing incident recently. i was verbally abused by someone i thought was a friend. you think you know someone well when you know them for a long time. but it is when problems and disagreements arise that you see them for what they really are.
all of us have good and evil within us. it is the side we choose to act upon that decides our worth. so when someone is pressurized
column2: the abuses they utter are intended to hurt you. the need to hurt you when they're hurt by you is natural. but the words they choose to hurt you determines their standard. if they've abused you once
column3: they'll do it again no matter how profusely they apologize. if it came easily for them the first time
column4: it'll come easier the second and the consecutive times. once that gets normalized
column5: they'll move on to physical abuse.

column1: here's ten cents from me - do not tolerate verbal abuses from anyone. do not encourage it. get as far away as possible from people who abuse you. you aren't entitled to be with them. years of friendship or love doesn't mean you have to tolerate verbal abuses. shun them. because if you don't react
column2: they'll do this to others too.

column1: if you notice that you or someone you know have or are developing the habit of swearing and using abuses
column2: stop right now. because once you get used to abusing
column3: it might not seem like a big deal to you. but it is a big deal for the listeners!

column1: 274523;instagram;2018-10-25 02:51:27;FALSE;"the last time i wore this shirt i was leaving the hospital after having my d&c procedure after my miscarriage.

it was an impulse buy after leaving one of my follow up appointments confirming the miscarriage or bloodwork - it‚Äôs a bit of a blur now - and i found myself reaching for it the morning of my procedure in june.

today i grabbed it and remembered our baby #3. about those long weeks of waiting for the inevitable. of how different every decision i make from what i eat to what my daily agenda is would be had it been a viable pregnancy.
just as quickly i snatched up my round toddler to meet my sweet mama friends for a play date followed by picking up my big girl from preschool where she sprints into my arms yelling
i kissed boo boos in this shirt today. i snuggled my big girl after her nap in this shirt today. i hugged my husband in this shirt today. i started and ended a great workout in this shirt today.

column1: 274586;instagram;2018-10-25 01:16:39;FALSE;"rant alert üö® i'm gonna be honest - it's difficult to teach kids about sexual harassment and appropriate boundaries in the context of today's political climate. this entire week has been filled with one sexual harassment allegation after another. a counselor at another school today told me how surprised she is that students seem to understand so little about sexual harrassment and healthy boundaries. at first i agreed with her
column2: but after thinking about it more deeply i am not surprised at all. young people
column4: are recieving conflicting and convoluted messages from people in power. how is it that we are supposed to hold ten and eleven year olds more accountable than the president of the united states and supreme court justices?! educators everywhere will keep doing it - one intervention at a time - but it's not easy or fun and sometimes it feels like an uphill battle. art by @nycchr.

column2: 1n5.org and wow has she survived so much and is thriving despite her circumstances! we have so much love for your

column1: my testimony is one so many can relate to because i have walked in the shoes of so many! i have fought anxiety
column4: anger problems and have contemplated killing myself on a number of occasions in the past!

column1: i do feel a lot of my issues stemmed from many different events in my life including having absent parents from the ages of 4 until 13
column2: knowing i had siblings in the world i had never met
column3: i was being raised by a family no relation to me and up until roughly 4 years ago never really had a relationship with my biological family.

column1: i was molested as a child
column3: i had a child at just 16 and then had to deal with the loss of the women that raised me at just 17 followed by being put in a foster home. but despite everything i had suffered i made it out!

column1: i graduated high school at the top of my class went on to college to get my bachelors degree in criminal justice and i now teach for one of our local schools as well as work part time. i have 2 children
column2: and what i would consider a successful career. i have mended the relationships with my parents. i have a decent relationship with all of my siblings
column3: even those who i did not grow up with and have put my ill feelings aside (in regards to my parents) to be able to grow both mentally and physically as both a women and mother!

column1: 274686;instagram;2018-10-24 23:25:32;FALSE;"sometimes i'd really like to guard myself against all the sexualization by strangers.
it was a really good day
column4: pictures of myself between fetish and adult content; i don't want to live in my past
column5: but it comes back to me way too often...

column1: and i do want to raise awareness for what people do
column2: when they misuse pictures and upload them in contexts they were never meant for. (besides a copyright infringement - because
column3: you aren't allowed to download or use pictures of others without their permission.)

column1: there were times when i wore a lot of leather clothing; to me
column2: it belonged to the heavy metal scene - i had a really innocent view of it. i wasn't well informed and never took fetishes really seriously - until i started modeling for a leather shop (which gave me some discounts on my stage wear) and suddenly found my pictures spread over the internet on pages
column3: i never wanted to imagine myself on
column4: with the nastiest comments i ever read.

column1: it is a horrible experience to be sexualized over and over again by strangers who describe their fantasies with you in details; it was truly disgusting. and even though it's only a ""comment to a picture""
column3: ""not in the real world"" - i am a real human being with real feelings - and all those things together made me feel used. in those situations
column4: i've been used for someone else's pleasure. you lose control over what people do to you - because yes
column5: it has to do with you when they see your picture; they don't care about you and your feelings
column8: the picture of your body. i've seen a lot because i tried to remove all pictures; it's not possible - they get uploaded over and over again. guys (and girls and non-binary folks)
column9: whenever you are on certain pages remember
column10: not all people you see there
column11: are there because they want to - most may not even know! it's emotionally devasting - and i ""only"" find pictures of me fully dressed; i don't want to imagine what it feels like for people who find videos etc. sexuality needs consent

column1: a very prominent difference between c-ptsd & ptsd is survivors' inclination to dissociate. this is true not only as a psychiatric symptom that many struggle with daily post-trauma
column2: but also something that was very active during the trauma. this survival mechanism can cause some really unique - & at times scary - experiences. one being the way that traumatic information gets stored and how it differs from regular memories. the pieces can get scattered
column4: non-cohesive narrative. survivors may even go a significant portion of their lives unaware they were traumatized at all
column5: recalling everything in great detail much later. memories may even be recalled out of chronological order
column8: or the ""wrong"" emotion. not only are trauma memories more likely to return via flashbacks & nightmares
column9: they can resurface as body memories & unexplained pain
column10: too - all thanks to dissociation. through therapy
column11: these pieces can be put together
column12: but initially they may confuse the survivor & even make them (& loved ones) question their integrity & honesty. .

column2: there's dissociation as a present ongoing symptom. dissociation is feeling detached from your body &/or thought processes. it exists on a spectrum & is something everyone does to a small degree (ie. daydreaming or highway hypnosis)
column3: but in c-ptsd it is much more pronounced. survivors may experience depersonalization (leaving your body
column4: feeling like a fly on the wall
column5: going on autopilot) or derealism (feeling as if you or your surroundings aren't real). they may struggle with just feeling fuzzy
column7: or in a fog more frequently. these experiences are more likely to occur in times of high stress or triggers
column8: just as the body learned to respond for years when it believed bad things were about to happen.

column2: there's a way through! grounding can be your primary defense (see our grounding 101 techniques article!)
column3: and therapy can walk you through the deeper levels of interrupted consciousness. you can absolutely feel more present & grounded & it is possible to make sense of your memories & life.";;en;;;;;;0;;beautyafterbruises;Beauty After Bruises;;0;False;7;0;0;226;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/15e94403ba93d7850349a6663bd1c359/5D26052B/t51.2885-15/e35/s1080x1080/43779451_738484903173862_6944645993376940143_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"‚úßc-ptsd criteria: part 2‚úß

column2: i swear i have artwork coming but i wanted to share. i feel like i have made leaps and bounds with healing from ptsd.  i realized it this past week after having to spend tons of time with someone who plays a role in my trauma. i can‚Äôt even believe i‚Äôm saying that because i knew i would heal but i never believed myself to be free. i always thought my abuser had a house right inside me and now it‚Äôs like it‚Äôs getting demolished and cleared. ironically
column3: quite literally i have to see the physical house every single day and it doesn‚Äôt phase me anymore. sure the foundation of it will always be there but i‚Äôm building something stronger and more worthwhile.

column1: even if something does arise it no longer knocks the wind out me it‚Äôs just a passing thought. i‚Äôm still processing a ton as it shows in my art work but for once i feel i can say my body is my own and i have my life back. this came from years of grueling
column3: emotional work. this work has to happen everyday. but it‚Äôs worth it

column2: and would be very striking if they re-released this in theatres today as a part of #metoo.

column1: all of you are falling in love with netflix's ""haunting of hill house""
column3: but take some time to see the first film outing of hill house. the original has a scientist studying the paranormal bringing two psychics into a potential haunted house. it's wild how scary this pg rated movie is. no blood
column5: just a sense of dread and some amazing sound work. a true classic.

column1: dive into the further as a family searches for answers inside their haunted home. combining great performances (horror icon lin shaye especially) and some truly stunning jump scares - the first film in the series created a mood that could never be captured in its sequels. well worth a revisit.
one of the best king movie translations (the third on my list already) mainly because it manages to capture how bleak and depressing the novel is. something's happening outside
column2: and a motley crew are stranded in a ma and pa grocery store waiting it out. the end of this film

column1: james wan's start to create his own multi-verse (and his 2nd appearance on the list). the warrens are the focus here and have been a part of the horror-verse ever since the amityville case blew the lid off of haunted houses. here we get great performances and a truly creepy game of clap clap.
stephen king appearing quickly again. yes
column3: and it's going to be tough to beat this. we have fred gwynne being creepy
column5: a walking head wound - and that's not even the scariest thing. one word to send shivers up your spine - zelda.";;en;#90

people listen?  are you clear about your boundaries in your relationships? do you feel the freedom to fully express yourself in life without being judged?  these are all your birthright along with
